South Africaâ€™s trade surplus in December widened to R15.72 billion ($1.33 billion) from a revised R13.05 billion surplus in November, data from the revenue agency showed on Wednesday. Exports fell by 10.2% to R104.32 billion on a month-on-month basis in December, while imports were down 14.1% to R88.6 billion, the South African Revenue Service said in a statement. On a cumulative basis the trade balance between January and December was at a R80.55 billion surplus compared to a R1.05 billion surplus over the same period in 2016. ($1 = R11.85)